The paper focuses on benchmarking in robotic manipulation research, which falls under the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The use of RGB-D scans and geometric models also suggests a potential overlap with computer vision (cs.CV). The paper also discusses the use of planning, learning, and control approaches, which are common in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) research. Finally, the manipulation problem involves the integration of hardware and software, which could fall under the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category.
